{
  "text": "For the face eye-height adaptation task, the method was as in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In the preadaptation phase (348 trials), participants viewed faces that varied in eye height (29 levels ranging from -24 pixels to +24 pixels; negative numbers indicate eyes shifted down from the unaltered \"zero\" face, and positive numbers indicate eyes shifted up from the unaltered face; Fig. 2a were \"high\" or \"low\" relative to their idea of a normal face. The postadaptation phase was the same except that each test face was preceded by a 4,000-ms adaptor face with an eye height of +50 pixels ( Fig. 2a ). Adaptor faces were smaller than test faces, to minimize contributions to the aftereffect from retinotopic low-level vision. For the CCMT, the method was as described in [CITATION_3] . The CCMT has the same structure, format, and scoring as the CFMT, but the stimuli are cars instead of faces (Fig. 4b) .",
